{"data":{"allContentfulBlogPost":{"edges":[{"node":{"id":"c1J5yJZB0GIY8EMWiOaKaCG","title":"Responsive Images and resizing.","tags":["SERVERLESS"],"description":{"id":"c1J5yJZB0GIY8EMWiOaKaCGdescriptionTextNode","description":"Optimising the sizes of your images gives your users a much better user experience. Here I share some useful tips on how to go about doing this. Also links on how facebook and medium have optimised their image loading for a better user experience."},"createdAt":"2018-01-13T08:04:23.127Z","blog":{"childMarkdownRemark":{"html":"<p>When we are building tech from scratch we go to work on some mundane but important things which may not be core to our product.</p>\n<p>Using an existing CMS system or an existing framework or a site generator makes a lot of things easy as they come built in with whats needed and hence we do not have to re-invent the wheel.</p>\n<p>But sometimes, when we are building something unique grounds up, we got to reinvent the wheel, but it is much easier now, as the smart folks have already figured it out and it is about understanding whats already figured out.</p>\n<p>One of these things is resizing images to make them responsive. </p>\n<p>Optimising the sizes and resolutions of our images gives our users a much better user experience. User experience is a loaded term and I will not get into that here. But rather will outline a few things about resizing images and making them responsive.</p>\n<p>There are typically two dominant use cases. The first one is when the image width is dependent on the screen width and the second one is when the image width is fixed, that is it will have the same width across all devices say - 300px on all screen widths.</p>\n<p>In both these cases, we will need to resize the images so it is optimised for multiple screen dimensions and <strong>screen resolutions</strong> (E.g Retina displays).</p>\n<p>Typically it suffices to create images with widths close to </p>\n<p>__1. 200px</p>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li>400px</li>\n<li>800px</li>\n<li>1600px</li>\n<li>2400px__</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If the image height is not fixed, then the image is resized maintaining the aspect ratio of the image.</p>\n<p>If the image height needs to be a factor of the width, then when the image is resized it is also cropped.</p>\n<p>The entire process of resizing the images to the appropriate sizes and cropping can be automated.</p>\n<p>I had hacked together such a piece, which created responsive images for me on the cloud. I used AWS Lambda to resize and crop the images. On Lambda imagmagick and sharp were the two options I had. I went with sharp as it was faster for the resizing use case.</p>\n<p>For the responsive code, I referred to the gatsby image plugin. The code is open sourced. The <a href=\"https://github.com/gatsbyjs/gatsby/tree/master/packages/gatsby-plugin-sharp\">gatsby image plugin</a> provides an easy interface to have responsive images on gatsby sites.</p>\n<p>The Img tag, instead of <code class=\"language-text\">src</code>, takes either <code class=\"language-text\">sizes</code> or <code class=\"language-text\">resolutions</code> as its props. The sizes is an object with srcset, src and sizes.\n(..and more):</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\">\n      <pre class=\"language-graphql\"><code class=\"language-graphql\"><span class=\"token string\">\"sizes\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n       <span class=\"token string\">\"srcSet\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"/static/rishikund-62f05.jpg 200w,\\n/static/rishikund sajdhar-dc2b4.jpg 400w,\\n/static/rishikund-381d6.jpg 800w,\\n/static/rishikund-14504.jpg 1024w\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n       <span class=\"token string\">\"sizes\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n       <span class=\"token string\">\"src\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"/static/rishikund sajdhar pic-e7e21d0046509e1f847cfef167ba624f-381d6.jpg\"</span>\n     <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>The resolutions is an object with srcSet along with the resolutions like 1x, 1.5x etc, src, width (..and more)</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\">\n      <pre class=\"language-graphql\"><code class=\"language-graphql\"><span class=\"token string\">\"resolutions\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">{</span>\n        <span class=\"token string\">\"srcSet\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"/static/rishikund-47df3.jpg 1x,\\n/static/rishikund-9f62f.jpg 1.5x,\\n/static/rishikund-34191.jpg 2x\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n        <span class=\"token string\">\"src\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token string\">\"/static/rishikund-47df3.jpg\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n        <span class=\"token string\">\"width\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token number\">400</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n        <span class=\"token string\">\"height\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token number\">266.796875</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span>\n        <span class=\"token string\">\"aspectRatio\"</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">:</span> <span class=\"token number\">1.499267935578331</span>\n      <span class=\"token punctuation\">}</span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>The gatsby image plugin uses the sharp library to create the image assests needed! It has a lot more going within it, in terms of making the image loading smooth. </p>\n<p>Gatsby itself, uses GraphQL to fetch the images to hydrate the react components. The GraphQL query to fetch a responsive image of a fixed width and height would be like the following:</p>\n<p>Here are a few good links which helped me better my understanding of responsive images and image loading.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/HTML/Multimedia_and_embedding/Responsive_images\">Good website to learn about responsive images</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://cloudfour.com/thinks/responsive-images-101-definitions/\">Responsive images, a very nice multi part series blog.</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://usecases.responsiveimages.org/\">This is a pretty long read. Use cases for loading images</a></p>\n<p>Below are the next steps, once you have resized your images.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://code.facebook.com/posts/991252547593574/the-technology-behind-preview-photos/\">This Facebook article is ðŸ’¯ They are powering this system through GraphQL ðŸ”¥</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://jmperezperez.com/medium-image-progressive-loading-placeholder/\">How medium does progressive image loading</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://css-tricks.com/the-blur-up-technique-for-loading-background-images/\">The blur up technique for loading background images</a></p>\n<p>In an upcoming blog, I will share how to resize the image using lambda and sharp with the code I used.</p>","timeToRead":4}},"featuredImage":{"title":"Camera","resize":{"src":"//images.ctfassets.net/ojam5vx77jn8/1nQCb9RDiMyqKWmeuCMou2/79d030b143755519eb8973436cfb75bb/mitchell-hollander-204781.jpg?w=1200&h=630&fl=progressive&q=50&fit=fill&f=faces"},"sizes":{"aspectRatio":1.5,"src":"//images.ctfassets.net/ojam5vx77jn8/1nQCb9RDiMyqKWmeuCMou2/79d030b143755519eb8973436cfb75bb/mitchell-hollander-204781.jpg?w=800&q=50","srcSet":"//images.ctfassets.net/ojam5vx77jn8/1nQCb9RDiMyqKWmeuCMou2/79d030b143755519eb8973436cfb75bb/mitchell-hollander-204781.jpg?w=200&h=133&q=50 200w,\n//images.ctfassets.net/ojam5vx77jn8/1nQCb9RDiMyqKWmeuCMou2/79d030b143755519eb8973436cfb75bb/mitchell-hollander-204781.jpg?w=400&h=267&q=50 